"It takes a lot of time to centralize mortality data," said Dr. Robin Blackstone, specialist in obesity surgery, who wrote an article about the new study in JAMA Surgery.
Operations for weight loss, called and bariatric surgery, use different methods to lower your stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the body's ability to absorb food.
Over the years, bariatric surgery has proved effective in the treatment of type 2 diabetes but most studies have been conducted on people with morbid obesity, with a body mass index (BMI) 35 or higher.
BMI, a weight measurement unit relative to height, is considered normal in the range 18,5-24,9.
The BMI value of at least 25 indicates that one person is overweight and people with BMI over 30 are considered obese.
You can calculate the BMI by accessing: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For the new study, researchers from the General Hospital Min-Sheng in Taiwan used the data narrow after 2007 in a trial comparing two types of bariatric surgery - bypass gastric and gastrectomy in the jaw - in the medical treatment of type 2 diabetes in people with mild obesity.
The mean BMI in patients with surgery decreased from 31 to 24.5 to the end of the fifth year of the study.
In the meantime, BMI in people receiving neurosurgery treatment against diabetes remained almost at the same level, namely 29.
Of those who had surgery, diabetes was completely cured by 36% and partly by 28%.
In the group treated by medical methods, by comparison, diabetes has been completely cured at only 1% and partly at only 2% of subjects.
In addition, the control of blood pressure, triglycerides and ‘bad’ LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgical group,” the authors concluded.
Researchers also monitored the level of haemoglobin A1c, which reflects the level of blood glucose over time.
Researchers say that the optimal level of haemoglobin A1c is below 7%.
Following surgery, the average haemoglobin level A1c decreased from approximately 9% to about 6%.
But in the medically treated group, it remained at approximately 8%.
But this improved “glycaemic control” - reflected by improved levels of A1c hemoglobin - did not reduce mortality to five years, according to the researcher chief Dr. Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The research team also compared the average results associated with the two types of surgery.
In the fifth year, compared with the gastroctomy group in manchon, the bypass surgery group lost more weight (18.7 compared to 14.2 kg), recorded more significant decreases in BMI (7.4 compared to 5.1) and haemoglobin A1c (3.1%) and presented a higher probability of complete remission of diabetes (46.9% compared to 16.7%).
Although the new study does not indicate a benefit in survival or surgery after five years, there is evidence from a study conducted on people with high weight in Sweden that surgery prolongs life, says Blackstone, from Arizona University, Faculty of Medicine - Phoenix.
In the Swedish study, obese people who underwent bariatric surgery presented a probability of approximately 29% lower death after 15 years, compared to a group that tried more conventional methods.
Although the new study did not indicate a benefit in survival in patients who underwent surgery, Blackstone said it was an optimistic aspect for people with BMI under 35 procedural interests.
“This is the point where this work is critical because it says that this surgery is safe in the lower BMI group,” she says, without increasing the risk of death or kidney disease.
Blackstone added that their patients and doctors should start taking the weight seriously then the BMI of the patient reaches 27-30.
